9–1529","1490–1520":"1490–1520","1500–1579":"1500–1579","1485–1550":"1485–1550","1579":"1579","1500":"1500","17 Mar 1529":"17 maart 1529","1520":"1520","c.1550":"circa 1550","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","Abt. 1485":"circa 1485","1529":"1529","1490":"1490","1449":"1449","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Sanderstead, Surrey, England":"Sanderstead, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Luddenden, Yorkshire, England":"Luddenden, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Yorkshire":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Sowerby in Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt. 1485–c.1550":"about 1485–about 1550","1449–1529":"1449–1529","1490–1520":"1490–1520","1500–1579":"1500–1579","1485–1550":"1485–1550","1579":"1579","1500":"1500","17 Mar 1529":"17 March 1529","1520":"1520","c.1550":"about 1550","1485":"1485","1550":"1550","Abt. 1485":"about 1485","1529":"1529","1490":"1490","1449":"1449","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Sanderstead, Surrey, England":"Sanderstead, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Luddenden, Yorkshire, England":"Luddenden, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Yorkshire":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Sowerby in Halifax, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wade","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Wade</i> (Old English <i>Wada</i> or, via Norman French, from ancient Germanic <i>Wado</i>, of unclear origin but possibly related to Old English <i>wadan</i> ‘to go’).","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>wade</i> ‘ford’ (Old English <i>(ge)wæd</i> ‘ford, especially a tidal crossing’) for someone who lived by a ford, or a habitational name from a place so called, such as Wade Hall in North Cove (Suffolk).","Irish: shortened and altered from <b>Mac Uaid</b>, see   McQuaid  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Wadeson","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Wade  ."]},{"name":"Wass","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Wace</i> (ancient Germanic <i>Waz(z)o</i>), a pet form of any of various ancient Germanic personal names beginning with <i>Wad-</i> (compare   Wade   1). The name <i>Wace</i> was common among the Normans, alongside the Parisian French variant <i>Gace</i>, and was latinized as <i>Wazo</i> (nominative), <i>Wazonis</i> (genitive).","English (of Norman origin): occasionally, perhaps a variant of   Vause   with vocalizing of initial <i>V-</i>.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>was(se)</i> ‘sharp, cutting’."]},{"name":"Waide","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Wade  .","German: variant of   Weide  .","Irish: shortened form of <b>Mac Uaid</b>, see   McQuaid  ."]},{"name":"Waddy","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Wadey</b>, perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Wady</i>, a pet form of   Wade  , or in northern England alternatively a shortened form of   Waldo  . The name may also be a variant of   Wilday  ."]},{"name":"McQuaid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colum, Nuala.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaid</b> ‘son of <i>Uad</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Scottish form   McQuate  ."]},{"name":"Waithe","meanings":["English:","either a topographic name from Old Norse <i>vath</i> ‘ford’, or a habitational name from a place so named, such as Waithe (Lincolnshire) and Wath (North and Yorkshire).","variant of   Wade  ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sowerby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places in northern England called <i>Sowerby</i>, including Sowerby Bridge (Yorkshire), Castle Sowerby (Cumberland), Brough and Temple Sowerby (Westmorland), Sowerby and Sowerby under Cotcliffe (North Yorkshire), and Sowerby near Inskip and Sowerby Hall in Dalton (Lancashire). The placenames derive from Old Norse <i>saurr</i> ‘mud, sour ground’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’. Placenames of identical origin are also found in Scotland (as <i>Sorbie</i> in Ayrshire, Dumfriesshire, and Wigtownshire, as <i>Soroba</i> in Argyll, and as <i>Soroby</i> on Tiree); also on the Isle of Man (as <i>Surby</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Sorsby","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): variant of   Sowerby  ."]},{"name":"Sowersby","meanings":["English and Scottish (Midlothian): variant of   Sowerby  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name 